Ag NPs were prepared by depositing a thin Ag layer (10 nm) on the ITO BRs or ITO film, followed by thermal annealing (Fig. 1a). When the 10 nm-thick Ag layer was deposited on ITO BRs, the Ag layer showed discontinuous particles due to nucleation of Ag atoms (Fig. 1b). In contrast, the Ag layer on the ITO film showed a network of islands (Supplementary information Figure S1). One possible reason for the enhanced dewetting of the Ag layer is the 3D geometry of ITO BRs. Typically, thin metal layers deposited on vertically aligned nanostructures form particle-like nuclei on the sidewalls of nanostructures due to the shadowing effect55. So, the shadowing effect can enhance the formation of Ag NPs on ITO BRs. In addition, line-tension plays a critical role in the dewetting of nanoscale metal particles. In line-tension theory, the contact angle of a small droplet is affected by the size of the NPs as follows9,10:cos(θ)=γSV-γSLγLV-τγLVr\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
